From 975474b12132795c682255657d91fb6cedc53581 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Gravio <gravio@uni-muenster.de>
Date: Thu, 30 Apr 2026 05:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] workbench: auto-load project_config.ini from CWD if found
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

When `mufasa` (or `mufasa-workbench`) is launched without an
explicit `--project` flag, walk up from the current working
directory looking for a `project_config.ini`. If found, auto-load
it. This eliminates the friction of typing the full path every
time you cd into a project to work on it.

Search behavior
---------------

Mufasa projects are laid out as:

  <project_path>/<project_name>/project_folder/project_config.ini

So discovery has to handle both cases:
  - User cd'd into project_folder/ or one of its subdirs (csv/,
    videos/, etc.) — config is in CWD or an ancestor
  - User cd'd into <project_name>/ but not project_folder/ —
    config is in CWD/project_folder/ (i.e. a subdir, not an
    ancestor)

At each level walking up, the helper probes BOTH `<level>/project_config.ini`
AND `<level>/project_folder/project_config.ini`. First hit wins.
Walk-up terminates after 3 levels to avoid picking up unrelated
projects from sibling trees in deep directory structures.

User-visible behavior
---------------------

- `mufasa` from inside a project_folder: auto-loads the project,
  prints `Auto-loading project config: <path>` to stderr so the
  user knows what happened (silent magic is bad UX, especially
  with multiple projects on one machine).
- `mufasa --project /explicit/path`: respects the explicit flag,
  no search.
- `mufasa --no-auto-discover`: skips the search even when CWD
  has a config. Useful for CI runners or wrapper scripts that
  want deterministic launch.
- `mufasa` with no config anywhere in the search range: behaves
  exactly as before (launches with no project loaded).

Why a depth cap of 3
--------------------

The plausible "deepest user CWD" is project_folder/csv/<some-stage>/
(e.g. `csv/features_extracted/`), which is 2 levels below the
config. Adding a level of safety margin gives 3. Going to 5 or 10
risks finding a sibling project's config when working in a deep
directory structure unrelated to mufasa.

Why announce to stderr instead of a popup
-----------------------------------------

Popups interrupt; stderr informs without blocking. The Qt event
loop hasn't started by the time discovery runs, and the user
will see the workbench window open with the project loaded —
the stderr line lets them double-check WHICH project if they
have multiple cd'd into recently.

What changed
------------

1. MODIFIED: mufasa/ui_qt/workbench_app.py
   - Adds _auto_discover_project(start) helper. Pure-stdlib,
     uses pathlib. Returns the closest project_config.ini
     found within _AUTO_DISCOVER_MAX_DEPTH (=3) levels up,
     or None.
   - Adds two module-level constants:
       _AUTO_DISCOVER_MAX_DEPTH (= 3)
       _PROJECT_CONFIG_FILENAME (= "project_config.ini")
       _PROJECT_FOLDER_NAME (= "project_folder")
   - Adds --no-auto-discover argparse flag (off by default)
   - main() routes through the helper when args.project is
     None and --no-auto-discover wasn't given. Prints
     `Auto-loading project config: <path>` to stderr on hit.

2. NEW: tests/smoke_workbench_auto_discover.py — 10 cases:
   - Config in CWD
   - User one level above project_folder/, config inside
   - User in project_folder/csv/ (config one up)
   - User 2 levels deep (e.g. csv/features_extracted/)
   - Discovery exactly at max_depth (boundary)
   - Does NOT discover beyond max_depth
   - Returns None when no config anywhere
   - Closest match wins when multiple ancestors have configs
   - Filesystem-root walk terminates cleanly (no crash)
   - main() in workbench_app correctly wires up the helper
     (--no-auto-discover flag, dispatch logic, stderr output)

Verified in sandbox:
- All 22 smoke tests pass (1 new + 21 existing)
- compile clean on workbench_app.py
- _auto_discover_project extracted via AST and exec'd into a
  pure-stdlib namespace (no PySide6 dependency for the test)

Cannot be verified in sandbox:
- That the auto-load actually works end-to-end via the running
  workbench (would need PySide6 + a real project tree)

Stack now at 54 patches:
  53. cython_kernel_wiring       (route production through _native)
  54. workbench_auto_discover    (this patch)
